answers.body_markdown:
There are several concepts here that are all different although they share some similar syntax. 

The standard way to refer to a `type Name = ...` definition is a type alias not a type shape

Firstly types only exist at compile time. So by definition nothing can depend on them at runtime. This means that the type alias `Person` person will not in any way exist in the compiled js. 

Classes have a dual nature, their name represents both a type (the instance type of the class) and a runtime value (the constructor function used to initialize the object). 

When you say `class DataCollection extends Person` what you mean is that, at **runtime** the class `DataCollection` needs to add to its prototype chain the prototype of `Person`. Since type aliases are erased during compilation, there is nothing for the class `DataCollection` add to its prototype chain making this statement nonsensical for a type alias (or an interface).

When you say `class DataCollection implements Person` you are asking the compiler to make sure that, at compile time, the `class DataCollection` has all the members with the appropriate types of the `Person` type. This is a purely compile time operation so using a type alias is fine here.


The `T` in `class DataCollection&lt;T&gt;` is a generic type parameter. Generic type parameters can be used to make a class reusable for multiple data types while preserving the information about the underlying type:

```ts
class DataCollection&lt;T&gt; {
    add(value: T) {}
}
var c = new DataCollection&lt;number&gt;();
c.add(1)
c.add(&quot;1&quot;) // error
```
[Play](https://www.typescriptlang.org/play/#code/MYGwhgzhAEAiYBcwGED2IQFNgIJaoDsAeAFQD5oBvAKGjujABNGAKANzBAFdMAuaEgEoqAX2piOAJ2jBoAXmgFMAdziIU6LDnzECXALYAjTJLItBAbmrAAdE1YBGQdbvMWAIgfvhAeh-QTSVRJIA)

Notice above that `T` was never used inside a runtime expression, it is only used in type annotation, we can never use `T` in an expression (ex `new T()` would be invalid). `T` is just there to check at compile time that some aspect of the class (a parameter, a member, a return value) is of a specific type specified when the class is instantiated (in this case `number` specified in `new DataCollection&lt;number&gt;`).


Sometimes we need a bit more information about `T`. For example we might want to have an `onAdded` member. This is where the `DataCollection&lt;T extends TYPE&gt;` comes in. It allows us to constrain `T` to be a sub-type of another specified type:

```ts
type WithAdd = { onAdd(): void }
class DataCollection&lt;T extends WithAdd&gt; {
    add(value: T) {
        value.onAdd(); // ok since onAdd is on the constraint of T
        value.onAdded(); // error since onAdded is not on the constraint of T
    }
}

class Person {
    name!: string;
    onAdd(): void { }
}
var cErr = new DataCollection&lt;number&gt;(); // error number does not have onAdd
var c = new DataCollection&lt;Person&gt;()
c.add(new Person())
c.add({ onAdd() { } }) // error not a Person 
```
[Play](https://www.typescriptlang.org/play/#)

The syntax `DataCollection&lt;T implements { name: string }&gt;` has no meaning in typescript. Since the `extends` in a constraint already deals with just types, there would really be no difference in meaning between saying `T` extends a type or `T` implements type. In both cases `T` would be a subtype of the specified type so having both would be confusing without adding any value. As to why `extends` was chosen over `implements` it&#39;s anybody&#39;s guess.

