Press F12 on your fiddle and check where the error comes from:

```
(index):61 Uncaught SyntaxError: Unexpected token export
```

Let&#39;s check what is at line 61 of index:

```
export default Accordion;
```

Now, why would that be an issue? Well, because *native* javascript modules have to be placed inside of script tags that are marked as `type=&quot;module&quot;`.
You are using requireJs, which seems to be importing your javascript file by simply placing the code from your file inside of &#39;window.onload&#39;, which results in this code:
```
&lt;script type=&quot;text/javascript&quot;&gt;//&lt;![CDATA[

    window.onload=function(){
      
const Accordion = {
  items: [],
  listeners: [],

  init() {
    const accordions = document.getElementsByClassName(&#39;accordion&#39;);

    Array.from(accordions).forEach((accordion) =&gt; {
      const items = accordion.getElementsByClassName(&#39;accordion-item&#39;);
      Array.from(items).forEach((item) =&gt; {
        const title = item.getElementsByClassName(&#39;accordion-title&#39;);
        title[0].addEventListener(&#39;click&#39;, () =&gt; {
          item.classList.toggle(&#39;open&#39;);
        });
        this.listeners.push(title[0]);
        this.items.push(item);
      });
    });
  },

  destroy() {
    this.listeners.forEach((listener) =&gt; {
      listener.removeEventListener(&#39;click&#39;, () =&gt; {});
    });
  },
};

export default Accordion;


    }

  //]]&gt;&lt;/script&gt;
```

So there is an `export` inside of a function... that is not valid syntax. Remove it and the code will run just fine.

If want to use native javascript modules, use the `import` syntax to import your module. [More info](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Statements/import).

